article.description:
This was supposed to be the year Portland outgrew its expansion-team image. Instead, the Fire took a leap
backward in a season-opening loss to New York.
article.headline: Portland begins season with big loss
article.linkText: Fire open season on downer, lose big to Liberty
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- This was supposed to be the year Portland outgrew its expansion-team image. Instead, the Fire took a leap backward in a season-opening loss to New York. Becky Hammon scored 22 points and Tari Phillips had 20 as the Liberty beat the mistake-prone Fire 84-62 Wednesday night. ''I want to apologize to our fans for our performance tonight,'' said Jackie Stiles, who led the Fire with 11 points. ''We need to play with a lot more heart and passion than we did tonight.'' Teresa Weatherspoon added 11 assists for New York (1-1), which fell behind 33-32 early in the second half but used a a 20-5 run to put the game away. Portland committed 24 turnovers, more than it had in any game last season, when the Fire went 11-21 and lost 17 of their last 20 games. The franchise record of 28 was set the year before, when the team joined the WNBA. Some of the bad passes and silly mistakes can be attributed to new point guard Ukari Figgs trying to get used to her teammates and the triangle offense put in by coach Linda Hargrove. Figgs, who helped lead the Los Angeles Sparks to the WNBA title last year, scored 10 points but had just one assist, and the Liberty had a 22-9 edge in that department. ''We just played a little bit faster than we should have,'' Figgs said. ''We need to take our time on offense.'' Portland also was breaking in two new starting forwards: LaQuanda Barksdale and DeMya Walker. Both played well only in spurts, and they were no match for the Liberty's front line of Phillips, Tamika Whitmore and Crystal Robinson. ''They have a great bunch of young players that are very, very athletic,'' Liberty coach Richie Adubato said. ''We just had veterans vs. inexperience in certain positions.'' Stiles got off just seven field goal attempts, making three; she averaged 12 shots a game last year, when she won the league's rookie of the year award. ''I take a lot of responsibility for this loss,'' Stiles said. ''I need to come out and be a lot more aggressive. That's my role, and I didn't do that tonight.'' The Fire opened the second half with a turnaround jumper from center Sylvia Crawley and a layup by Stiles to take a one-point lead, but they soon reverted to last year's form, when they blew several second-half leads. Phillips scored eight points during New York's 20-5 run, which ended with a layup by Robinson after Portland's Carolyn Young turned it over in the backcourt. A putback by Vickie Johnson made it 55-40. Most of the enthusiastic crowd of 9,386 stuck around until the end. ''Hopefully, we won't allow something like that to happen again on our home court,'' Hargrove said. Game notes
Barksdale had eight points after scoring just two all last season, when she missed 15 games with a back injury. ... Portland made five of its first seven shots but then went 5-for-20. ... New York center Camille Cooper came down with food poisoning Tuesday night and didn't play.
